Package sailpoint.object

Class Form.Section

  • java.lang.Object
    • sailpoint.tools.xml.AbstractXmlObject
      • sailpoint.object.Form.Section
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, FormItem, sailpoint.tools.xml.PersistentXmlObject
    Enclosing class:
    Form
    public static class Form.Section
extends AbstractXmlObject
implements FormItem
    Forms use sections to organize sets of fields. In theory sections can contain subsections to define layout, not using that yet. The model and Formicator support nested fields but the editor and renderer do not.
    See Also:
    Serialized Form

    • Field Detail

      • TYPE_DATA_TABLE

        public static final java.lang.String TYPE_DATA_TABLE
        Type that causes the section to be rendered as a two column table with non-editable fields. This is typically used for informational tables to give the form filler outer some context so they know what they are doing.
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • TYPE_TEXT

        public static final java.lang.String TYPE_TEXT
        Type that causes the section to be rendered as non-bordered text. If the section has more than one field, they are rendered with breaks in between. This is used for information text, often at the top of a page but can also appear between form sections to provide instruction.
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • getPriority

        public int getPriority()
        Description copied from interface: FormItem
        A number that influences the ordering of fields and sections when assembled into a form for presentation. The default is zero which means the form assembler is free to put it anywhere, normally they will be appended to the parent section. If a number is set, the form assembler will put fields with a lower number above those with a higher number. Best practices are still being developed, but one built-in rule is that the plan compiler will assign a default priority of 10 to any fields that come from an account creation template. In the typical case this will make creation fields appear above fields that came from role templates which is usually what you want. Start by considering the range 1-9 for special system use, the range 10-19 for account creation templates and 20+ for role templates. These are simply guidelines, templates writers are free to violate them.
        Specified by:
        getPriority in interface FormItem

        public boolean isHidden()
        Return whether this section is hidden. This is a pseudo-property that looks at Field.ATTR_HIDDEN in the attributes map.
        Throws:
        java.lang.RuntimeException - If the hidden attribute is a DynamicValue and the form has not yet been expanded.

      • isWrapper

        public boolean isWrapper()
        Return true if this is a wrapper section, meaning it doesn't define any significant properties for rendering and it contains a FormRef in it's item list. Wrapper sections can be removed and the contained FormRef merged with the parent. This is used when assembling FormRef's after the introduction of Sectionless forms in 7.0.
